27 September update: Eleventh update (see tenth update at [1]) of my Guesstimate model [2] of the top 50 most populous countries other than the US and Brazil exceeding 1M cases by the end of the year. I've combined this with the use of a normal distribution calculator [3] with a standard deviation of 1.5. I've also changed some of the probabilities of individual countries based on new case data [4] from the last week.

Taking current cases and adding (10-day moving average * days remaining this year) to get projected cases. There are two countries (Russia and India) that have already hit 1 million cases. There are six more (Colombia, Peru, Spain, Mexico, Argentina, and France) projected to hit 1 million, giving a total of 8. There are a few countries currently spiking (UK, Iraq, Indonesia, and Israel) that need to be watched closely, but UK (928460) is the only one of these currently projecting anywhere near 1 million cases. Weighting heavily towards 7, 8, or 9 countries.

Still shocking to me how badly the crowd is handling this question. It's been obvious this question was going to be in the top two options since August 1st. All you have to do is download the data from the resolution site. Filter it by today's or previous days date and do a simple linear calculation: Current total + (yesterday's cases * remaining days). Remaining days is 104 today. You do that, below is the result for countries with a calculation above 500,000. While it doesn't account for the effects of places that will go into lockdown, such as Israel or the U.K., it also doesn't account for seasonality or increased testing capacity. And yet, the crowd is just 29% in the top two options. And, this doesn't even require getting your mind around exponential growth. This is a linear calculation.

109 days to go. For those countries at 500k this needs an average of 4.6k per day to reach 1m. Many countries are in this range. Already hit 1m = 2: India and Russia ( in addition to US and Brazil) Over 500k = 6: Peru, Colombia, Mexico, South Africa, Spain, Argentina. Over 400k = 2: Iran and Chile Then there are a group of EU countries all getting spikes of high number of new cases at the moment. For example, France has 373k cases so far. To get to 1m they would need 5k cases per day every day until the new year. Current average is closing in on 10k per day, which reduces the future average needed. So while low probability, it is not out of the realms of possibility for France to hit 1m cases by end of the year.

Per @pstamp there are 2 countries already at the threshold and another 4 at 80% or better chance of the threshold. This question is therefore about how many "more" countries will pass the threshold. I argue that there will be at least 1 more and maybe as many as 3 more that cross the 1M threshold by year end. As we have seen holidays or state events are enough to trigger superspreader events that can last a long time. Some have argued that more testing will expose more cases.

1 August update: Significantly revising my probability distribution toward bin 4 based on a re-evaluation of my implicit model. I've put some more thought into how to evaluate the combined probabilities I assign to the top 50 most populous countries and for this purpose I have made a model using Guesstimate [1] — the results of which is a mean of 7.5 (95% CI: 5.6, 9.4) countries exceeding 1M cases by the end of the year. However, I think this 95% CI is much too confident so instead of assuming a standard deviation of 1 I've used a normal distribution calculator [2] to assume a standard deviation of 2.5 so that ~55% instead of 95% of the probability distribution falls in the 5.6-9.4 range, which sounds much more plausible given the large amount of uncertainty we have. The values I've assigned to each bin assumes a normal distribution using these values. Also note that I've also changed some of the probabilities I've assigned to individual countries based on some more reading I've done about their current situations. And finally, big thanks to @jainsa for his commentary — I always welcome critical analysis that has the potential to help me make better forecasts!
